These "community-based research practices" make the science both more humane and more rigorous.

First, there is the concern that scientists will be biased. We bring our own biases to the hypotheses we propose & the way we interpret our results. The solution to that, however, is not "stop this science," but partner with the people you are studying.

For the meta-science people - can we have less of this and more things like 'how to persuade people to apply FDR correctly" or "what are the key things in pre-registration that need to be present" or "is it valid+sensible to share clinical trial data for hypothesis generation"

These big "size of pie" and "how to slice the pie" questions are a very different class of questions from "is this science the best we can fund now in this area" or "has this institute delivered over the last 5 years".

There are some other big resource allocation questions - how much money into different areas of science; subfields; resources/hypothesis generation vs testing ; directed vs curiosity lead. But here any cross-field ranking metric is truly useless - it is quite simply meaningless.

And when do we need to rank scientists or science? There are times, but rarer than one realises - in grant reviews to give out money; in assessments for promotion; for prizes (a bit of an odd thing); in assessments for departments or institutes.

Is this fair? sensible? What to do? In my view - what to do if you "need" to rank/assess scientists is you get unconnected scientists to ... read, review and rank scientists. Average of 5 unbiased opinions will be pretty good and way better than all this pseudo-quantitative stuff

(This is compounded in human genetics by this consortium author scheme that gets expanded now in some biblometrics, rather than... plain ol' citation of the original paper. Can we stop consortium style authors on derivative papers to indicate data sharing?)

It also reveals so much about citation practice: long standing methods often cited (fair enough?) though often databases not cited (assumed to be there) or data items. Genomics, Human Genetics and Human Cancer genomics have mega-author lists.

Biblometrics even at their very best will only work to crudely help distinguish "broadly good" science from "bad, low productivity science". Even then - its dubious. Using them to rank the top end of science is just ... mindless in my view (and what does it even mean!)

MLE corresponds to MAP with uniform priors for your current coordinates. So the reparameterized MLE corresponds to a new MAP with an implicitly *different* set of uniform priors. I can't decide whether this makes MLE or MAP stranger.

A subtler point, maximum likelihood estimates (MLE) and maximum a posteriori (MAP) differ in this respect. MLE is invariant to change of variables since the likelihood is *conditioned* upon those variables, so the mode doesn't change. Posterior modes do change.

We need good structures to make these decisions (the UK HFEA is a good structure here, others around the world; some other countries... in particular the US in my view... need to move to something similar). Debate must start now to be ready for the growing ability of science

But - go forward 5 or 10 years what should this list be? How much does society restrict choices vs parents? If there is a list (I think there should be!) what are the criteria, how confident does one have to be in outcomes and who determines this?

Note: today in most countries parents are allowed to have information on chromosomal abnormalities (eg, Down's syndrome as Laura eloquently discusses) and in the context of PGD, certain single gene disorders, eg, CFTR, Sickle Cell
(For NIPT this is because enough foetal DNA is shed from the placenta into the mother's blood, and has characteristics which allow one to sort out by and large from the mother's DNA)

The generic, worldwide question is what type of genetic information should parents be allowed to act on, both for PGD and Non Invasive Pregnancy tests (NIPT) which is likely to extend its ability to look "deeper" into the foetus' genome from a blood test on the mother.

I'm better now at drawing my red lines (no raw snails and no horsemeat!) and even the simplest well made miso soup is great to me.

Sushi-wise I am a fan, happy with roe (of different types) and sea urchin. I love the "Tokyo style" ("Edo sushi") - a bed of rice, often season with soy+wasabi just right from the chef.  It's only the sea snails which I baulk at.

The food is very protein heavy often with heavy umami (meaty; soy sauce) flavour - but can also be light (I was ticked off multiple times about tempura in soy sauce - good tempura only needs the lightest touch of salt).

As well as being lovely, there is something deeply clean and right about Japanese food. The emphasis is on taste and texture, not at all on volume, and the natural rhythm of how food arrives, eating with chopsticks and discussion with chef means it all happens at a good pace.

This goes from the sushi bar in tsukiji, to the tiny restaurant in okazaki to the amazing "hackers" bring your own dinner in Tokyo (with filleted fish in front of us, tempura, smoked wild boar from Chiba, a bakery schedule worthy of TV and shabi-shabi beef)
There is some combination of the art of everyday actions plus the cleanness plus the attention to detail that makes nearly every aspect of Japanese cuisine a pleasure.
Final thread - Japanese food. The food.... It is simply amazing.

@US_FDA said it is still committed to advancing a regulatory framework for diagnostics, including LDTs, via legislation, but that the agency will step in to regulate when there is a public health risk.

The actions raise historic antagonisms between lab industry and @US_FDA about the agency's authority to regulate lab testing services. FDA maintains it can regulate LDTs as devices, industry disagrees and has thwarted the agency's attempts to lift "enforcement discretion" to date https://t.co/IuTcFXQEKr

This is one of a whole series of experiences that summer (I met pastors; spent time with an unmarked police unit; visited Alex Brown+Legg Mason same day as west Baltimore) that completely changed my understanding of African American life

The teachers never quashed this fantasy but were patient and consistent in bringing him back to the everyday- that he was making progress, and that learning to read was a good thing whatever his future

I was assigned to a charming man, my age, who had built an elaborate story of how he was going to escape West Baltimore, make his fortune, marry a beautiful woman and have his own house with a porch in the suburbs. This story started with him learning how to read.
(That the education system was so systematically biased and bad for African Americans was simply breathtakingly shocking even more so now I am older, have my own children etc)

It‚Äôs hard not to cry or rage as one understands the African American story; probably the most heart rending moment was when I spent two days with the adult literacy project in Baltimore. Exceptionally dedicated and patient teachers helping grown men and women learn how to read
When I worked in the Mayor‚Äôs office in Baltimore, just before I started my PhD it was the start of a still on going education into African American history and culture.

Tomatillos are extreme outcrossers,  so all I had to do to make my initial cross was to grow one plant of each parental variety next to each other and let the bees help me with the details.

Most of my genetics experiments have been pretty simple, with the traits reassorting in expected patterns (at least when I can identify genes to follow through a cross).My tomatillo breeding project is turning out to be a bit more complicated.

It was some 40 years after Mendel's 1865 publication that linkage was identified, again from studies with peas (by Bateson and Punnett (of Punnett square fame)).This was observed by more of the F2 (2nd gen after cross) progeny than expected carrying two parental traits.

Mendel intentionally chose the traits he went on to publish about. This is not the same thing as cherry-picking data, or any sort of dishonesty. It was isolating simple, comprehensible cases for detailed study.

Rep. @louiseslaughter was determined to pass this bill. She first introduced it to Congress in 1995, which failed that year. For 13 years, she continually went to Congress with new versions until it passed in 2009. https://t.co/zMf36Vq3wn

Why was #GINA important? Research consistently showed that some people with a high risk for hereditary diseases would forgo potentially life-saving genetic testing because they were afraid of possible discrimination. #GINA was intended to remove that concern.

But what's #GINA? It's a federal law that prevents health insurers and employers from discriminating against you based on your genetic info. Rep. Slaughter wanted to remove the fear of losing your job or health insurance when taking genetic tests https://t.co/HaamgbmLO7 https://t.co/XeSP0TD7Ya

Rep. @louiseslaughter was the only microbiologist in Congress. Her expertise and success in advocating for breast cancer research and the inclusion of women and minorities in biomedical research led to her working on a genetics non-discrimination bill. üì∑Jamie Germano https://t.co/Sq2r1ANAMt

It is so important that we recognize ideas and originality are funny things. The source of inspiration isn't a straight line of the lone genius. And, the best science is done as teams where we all learn and grow. 9/

I can see it now looking back at my early work in weather prediction -- I came up with the model for non-locality in this paper. That was originally mine, even if my graduate advisor pushed me in the direction of the original idea of the project. https://t.co/1xuVVVO5lX 8/
As mentors, how often does that spark of new ideas from our trainees push us in new directions. Yet, we get the glory and our trainees lose sight of how they sparked the idea. 7/
But, looking through the lens of a mentor now. I see my thought that this was my "first original paper" is so untrue. Yes, it was my first guided project but not my first original one. 6/
Breaking down the fear to publish my own work remains another reason this is perhaps one of the papers I'm most proud of. 5/

But, this paper was published 2 years after we finished the work. Why? Because I took critical comments from a well meaning colleague to push the work to the next level as a sign that it wasn't a good area to pursue and doubted myself. 4/

How should such a large, likely dominant, multi-layered, aligned political Europe treat mid-sized countries in Europe that don't want to be part of this? This is the rub. There are enough intelligent, wise people to see mutual benefit. The question is whether they are in charge

For federal countries - such as Germany and Spain (and could be UK)- arguably this is simply "one more layer". For small European countries this is necessity. For large, unified countries, this will be a change, but one for European solidarity and one hopes future prosperity

All said and done though, the EU is in a far better position when its monetary world (Euro) is aligned to its fiscal world (EU budget) and is aligned to its politics (European Council +European Parliament). This is, by definition on the first question of the Euro, without the UK.

<< the silly idea of some sort of release from the chains of the EU that the Tory party tout is madness even on the trade side as an amateur economist - its *complete* madness on the science side; we have no chains! Another example of false, pointless rhetoric)

(For the UK audience - there is nothing "holding the UK back" in the current EU structure on science - formally science doesn't not have the restrictions of going through the EU that trade has, and the UK science community is European and International >>

EMBL itself - European but separated from the EU - is a good example, as is CERN, but these are only small parts of the broad and deep interlinking of science across Europe, and the EU is a big part of knitting science together across the European continent.

Back to science. Science is fundamentally international; scientific cooperation is less bound than trade (legally it is a very separate bucket than trade in the EU) so it is hard to imagine there will not be some types of scientific cooperation and collaboration, whatever Brexit

As a Brit, I apologise deeply for this - I don't think so many Brits totally get the break in trust this has caused - and genuinely I will fight every point for a sensible, fair, open UK, whatever the next the steps over the coming months (years).

Even more so for the 3 million European citizens who have made their home in the UK and now found their host country arbitrarily change the basis of their relationship and infused the politics with anti-immigrant, selfish and ultimately uncaring rhetoric and practicality

As someone who has consistently said that I am proud Brit and a committed European - and refuses to claim these are contradictions - its been personally very emotional - and it's not going to end soon.

A particular frustration is that even inside of the UK, Brexit is as much about identity, nostalgia and internal British angst as it is about the UK's relationship to EU or its relationship to its nearest neighbours (most notably the Republic of Ireland).

Brexit is a ... real, and deepening, mess, made from British politics and a subpart of British politics at that; It is almost impossible that the UK will get a better (or even broadly similar) relationship to the rest of the EU as it does now.

Lichtenberg figures on the skin are pathognomonic for lightning strike!

Recall that Ohm's law states current (I) in a circuit is proportional to the voltage (V) and inversely proportional to the resistance (R). So your high resistance skin is trying to protect you from getting massive current flow through your internal organs (which would be bad).

Your skin acts as an insulator -- it can have resistance up to 100,000 ohms according to the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.  But at high voltages, the skin begins to break down and the resistance drops.

This work opens the door to cultivation efforts of other Asgard archaea. Characterisation of common and specific features of Asgards, especially of those closer related to eukaryotes, will be paramount for refinement of eukaryogenesis models.

The phylogenetic support for Loki+eukaryotes reported in this manuscript is in line with recent reports from several labs (including my own group), but needs to be carefully assessed with regard to more robust phylogenetic methods and better taxonomic sampling.

Loki cells seemingly lack intracellular features, suggesting that Loki ESPs such as actin, profilin and gelsolin homologs are involved in membrane remodelling (e.g. formation of protrusions). Important to note that Loki lacks ESPs such as TRAPP, Sec23/24 & coatamer homologs.

Loki cells are relatively small (~0,5 um), and produce unique, membrane-based protrusions of unknown function, possibly involved in sustaining syntrophic interactions, or cell attachment. Small cell size is in line with previous report from Knittel et al https://t.co/ZgZBrd0gG9

The COMPLETE Loki genome confirms that it closely matches with Loki MAGs that were previously published by several labs. Hence, eukaryotic-like genes ("ESPs") NOT the result of binning contamination as suggested by some.

You definitely can't do it on your own though- you'll need backup. Hence the safety net.I really wish I could give cut and dry advice here...but if I could I wouldn't be dealing with some of what I'm dealing with now.

There's unfortunately no one surefire situation to handle conflict and issues in your program. If your issue is with your advisor, with other students, with other faculty- even within these, it can be hard to figure out the right course.

Respect your limits on dealing with the situation, and make sure you know your options- up to and including exit strategies.I find just having a plan and options at different thresholds helps a lot, but this is very different by situation.

If things are really bad, evaluate the situation on a regular basis. Currently, as I am stuck in the middle of some high-grade bullshit, I do this monthly, listing both positive and negative developments, and taking steps as appropriate.

This is especially important given that bullying and harassment can come from any level, from other students on up to senior faculty. The people who can actually affect change on your behalf will vary based in part on that.

Different people in this safety net will have different abilities to help you- keep that in mind. Junior faculty and students may not be able to tackle big departmental stuff, but can be important sounding boards and allies.

There's unfortunately a myriad of Bullshit that will show up to make your life a mess. This is a big part of why forming your network of people you trust- students, faculty, and otherwise- is so important. They're your safety net.

I can fix this with blue/red LED tubes designed for plants. I'll keep one regular white LED bulb to fill in some of those middle frequencies that we like. (Also, some plants need those frequencies for growth regulation too.)
But... those lights don't output the high level of red light the plants also want. So, it isn't the amount of blue light per se, but the relative amount of blue to red that is probably the issue.

I've reassessed that theory. The commonly available white LEDs are made by layering a yellow phosphor on a blue LED. The combination of blue and yellow light looks white to us and there's enough red and other frequencies for things to look ok to us.
